### Why the strip is getting cropped

| Element | Aspect‑ratio | What it means |
|---------|--------------|---------------|
| **Container** (`.cover-card`) | `3 / 4` (0.75) | Width ÷ Height = 0.75 → *wider* than it is tall |
| **Image** (`<img>`) | `9 / 16` (0.5625) | Width ÷ Height = 0.5625 → *taller* than it is wide |

`object‑fit: cover` tells the browser to **scale the image so that the container is completely filled**.  
If the container is wider than the image (as in this case), the image is scaled to fill the width and the **height is cropped** – that’s why you see only a middle band of the strip.

---

## Fixes

You have two clean options. Pick the one that best matches your design intent.

| Option | What it does | When to use |
|--------|--------------|-------------|
| **1. Match the container’s aspect‑ratio to the image** | Set the container to the same ratio as the strip (`9 / 16`). | If you want the strip to fill the card exactly, no letter‑boxing. |
| **2. Keep the container’s ratio but change the fit** | Use `object-fit: contain` (or `scale-down`). The whole image will be visible, with empty space on the sides or top/bottom. | If you prefer to show the entire strip and are okay with “letter‑boxing”. |

### 1. Matching the aspect‑ratio

```css
/* Only apply to photo‑strip cards – e.g. add a modifier class or data‑attr */
.cover-card.photo-strip {
    aspect-ratio: 9 / 16;          /* 0.5625 */
    /* keep the rest of your styles */
}

.cover-card.photo-strip img {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: cover;             /* now it matches the container */
}
```

If you can’t add a modifier class, you can use a data attribute:

```html
<div class="cover-card" data-ratio="9/16">
    <img src="strip.jpg" alt="">
</div>
```

```css
.cover-card[data-ratio] {
    aspect-ratio: attr(data-ratio);
}
```

> **Tip** – If the board shows many different card types, keep the default `aspect-ratio: 3/4` and only override it for strips.

### 2. Using `object-fit: contain`

```css
.cover-card {
    aspect-ratio: 3 / 4;          /* keep the existing ratio */
}

.cover-card img {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    object-fit: contain;          /* shows the whole image */
    /* optional: center it */
    object-position: center;
}
```

This will leave empty space (usually a background color) on the top/bottom of the card, but the strip will never be cut off.

