The root cause is iOS Safari’s (and thus WKWebView’s) automatic text zoom on focus when an input field has a font size smaller than **16px**. Even though your `.desk-input` uses `font: inherit`, if the computed font size ends up below 16px, iOS triggers a page zoom to improve readability—this is a built-in accessibility feature.

**Fix:**  
Set the input’s font size to **at least 16px**:
```css
.desk-input {
  font-size: 16px; /* or inherit from a parent with >=16px */
}
```
Or, if you must keep the smaller visual size but prevent zoom, you can disable the behavior via:
```css
input, textarea {
  font-size: 16px;
  /* Visually scale down if needed using transform (advanced) */
}
```

**Accessibility Tradeoff:**  
Forcing a minimum 16px font improves accessibility for most users (better readability), but if the design relies on compact inputs, it may increase vertical space usage or feel inconsistent on dense UIs. Avoid disabling zoom entirely—it helps users with low vision.

